          "title": "The faithful Creator — the chapter's closing rest",
          "body": "The whole chapter converges on one verb in 4:19: *paratithēsthōsan* — *let them entrust* (commit, deposit). The same verb Jesus used from the cross: *Father, into Your hands I commit (paratithemai) My spirit* (Luke 23:46). Peter, who watched it happen, presses the same verb on his readers. The object of entrustment is *psuche* — the soul, the whole life. The recipient is named with the chapter's freshest title for God: *pistos ktistēs* — *faithful Creator*. The NT uses *ktistēs* of God only here. Peter chooses it deliberately — the One who *made* the soul can be trusted to *keep* it through fire. The participle that closes the verse, *en agathopoiia* (\"in doing what is right\"), refuses the option of paralyzed despair. The suffering believer is not passive; he continues to do good while entrusting outcomes. This is the chapter's resting place."
